Independent schools in Scotland maintain academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, which only reinforces with individual and group success in sports, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as global citizens.
As an educational center that can design and implement customized school programs, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desirable as an elective subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it will make him imaginary.
If you speak to him in his language, it will strike him in the soul.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that languages outperform all other subjects with the highest success rate in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher score of “5+”.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher score of “5+” in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those learning German, 69 percent of those learning French, and 63 percent of those learning Spanish also achieved “5”.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly acquire in the future.
Languages now, as an elective subject, are seen at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in the programs of independent schools, as well as elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the Employment and Skills Commission of the OK noted that of the reasons employers cited for failing to fill jobs, 17 percent were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more compulsory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs looking for languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career one chooses, if they learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give the polyglot an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults from OK in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to speak, and French was the only language spoken by over ten percent, i.e. 15 percent of people.
Therefore, investing in language learning is now important for today’s children.
Having more languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with better chances of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ according to the languages it teaches.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important in OK when viewed in the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child’s interests are, there will always be numerous languages to choose from in independent schools, with professors who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing an environment of learning that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied, in the global business environment, that languages will continue to be vital to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in schools.
In fact, modern languages really should be regarded as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
"It has to be done" (it has to be done).
