Harvard students attend courses to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year aims to teach all graduates more sleep in order to combat the growing macho-culture of learning by staying awake all night with the help of caffeine.
One researcher found that students at the world’s leading university often don’t know anything about basic self-care.
Charles Chaizler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women's Hospital, designed the course he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a speech about the impact of insufficient sleep on learning.
“At the end of the lecture, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in the last year?’
She said no one, ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told Telegraph.
The course, which was offered for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help in academic and athletic performance, and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barrera, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part there is a picture of a student home where students press on coffee cups, curtains, shoes and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how insufficient sleep affects athletic performance and the importance of routine when going to bed.
In another part, participants learn about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart and stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know about the health effects when you choose to smoke a cigarette.”
The culture of pride in “work all night” still exists, he said, and besides modern technology and increasing pressure on students mean that lack of sleep is a growing problem.
To have enough sleep, with good quality, should be the student's "secret weapon" in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid obesity, because lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, which makes them constantly hungry.
Raymond Saw, a 19-year-old California student in chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaizeller design the course after attending one of his classes last year, in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to act as a course throughout the student city.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all postgraduates to complete a similar program before joining the competitive institution.
