New information on the red tide: Concentrations are falling in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red-water concentrations in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven algal blooms have been observed in the areas of the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the red algae shearing, extends about 130 miles off the coast from the northern Pinellas County to the southern Lee County.
Parts of the red tide can also be seen about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but the number is still lower compared to last week.
Red tides have also been observed in the district of Pasco.
During the past week, the following concentrations have been observed: average concentrations in or on the coast of the county of Pinelas, low to high concentrations on the coast of Hillsborough County, common to high concentrations in or on the coast of the county of Sarasota, high to low concentrations on the coast of the county of Pinelas.
In the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Li and Collier, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwestern Florida during the past week.
